		<title>Access native OS installs?</title>
		<link>http://androw.is/blog/access-native-os-installs</link>
		<comments>http://androw.is/blog/access-native-os-installs#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 02 Jan 2010 22:38:51 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Andrew AbuMoussa</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Mental Graffiti]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Operating Systems]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://androwis.com/blog/?p=58</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[and how to make your computers work for you by connecting to a home server...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Let&#8217;s start from the beginning&#8230; Being a programmer, computers have become an integral part of my life.  Up until the new year I had been trying to use a desktop and laptop with &#8220;identical&#8221; setups to complete my work.  Notice the &#8220;identical&#8221;;  that is what I wanted to fix for the new year. Both of my computers were dual booting mac and linux and each had a shared data partition accessible to each OS.  Well, the problem was that I got tired of juggling files, settings, programs and sync utilities trying to get the data and applications to match up on both (read &#8220;identical&#8221;).<br />
The requirements for the project formed pretty naturally:</p>
<ul>
<li>Have a unified store of data</li>
<li>Have said store accessible to any computer on my home network (ultimately any computer with internet)</li>
<li>Have the computers handle any of 3 major OS&#8217;s for software development reasons</li>
<li>Big time bonus:  If there were a way to virtualize each native install of an OS in the other two, you would reach OS zen.</li>
</ul>
<p>So, having a load of free time I decided to restructure and clean up my computing environment.  Ultimately what this meant was to install Windows after a 6 year hiatus, and move my two (theoretically) identical data partitions that were on each computer I was using to one single data folder hosted by a server.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s what I did.<br />
1) Set up a triple boot system with a shared data partition (I know the post is trying to convince you to lose that partition, but I set one up just in case for offline storage).  This isn&#8217;t a how-to of how to do that, but GPartedLive is by far the best tool to use.</p>
<p>2) Set up the server that acts as a NFS file server (what I think is the most accessible solution to all OSs, though requires some linux know-how) and a web server.  I chose to do this rather than buy a NAS server or some other solution becaarounduse it&#8217;s 1) more cost efficient to just use an old computer lying around and 2) it&#8217;s nice to minimize clutter by not having single purpose products lying around everywhere.</p>
<p>3)Finally, I configured the installs, unified the OS&#8217;s to have similar backgrounds, desktops, workflow, etc&#8230; but most importantly, set up access to the servers.  Here&#8217;s how to access NFS shares on different OSs after you add your computers to/etc/exports and make sure the shared directories are CHMODed 777:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>Windows 7</strong></em></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">This one&#8217;s easy.  You&#8217;ll see a &#8220;Map network drive&#8221; icon right under the address bar when you press the My Computer icon.  Click it.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Map.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-76" title="Map" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Map-300x220.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="220" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Pick what letter you want the drive to be mapped to, and then put the address in, and have it reconnect at login.  Done.<br />
<a href="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/win7.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-66" title="win7" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/win7-1024x575.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="449" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>Mac OSX </strong></em></p>
<p>Mounting an NFS share on mac is fairly simple.  There are two ways to do this.  1st the computer will show up under shared on the left.  You can login as a user on that server, and that&#8217;s that or you can auto-mount it by using the advanced features in the Directory Utilities under Settings : <a href="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/mac.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-70" title="mac" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/mac-1024x575.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="449" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>openSUSE (really any linux distro)<br />
</strong></em></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Add the following to the /etc/fstab:</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">serverNameOrAddress:/shared/folder    /mount/to/folder    nfs    rw,user,noauto,hard,intr 0 0<a href="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/linux.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-63" title="linux" src="http://androwis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/linux-1024x575.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="449" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: left;">There you have it&#8230; a unified data store environment across a bunch of computers&#8230; The beauty of this setup is that it is the most natural and accessible solution to unifying data stores.  By having all the data in one spot accessible to any computer, version control becomes insignificant for the single user (not considering simultaneous access by multiple users).  Backup becomes simplified and an overall sense of relief is afforded from solving that problem.  Second, it&#8217;s a beautiful way to unclutter your computers, providing a minimalist approach to data storage.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">So the two things that are missing are virtual machine access to native OS installs.  Secondly, a way to propagate changes of an OS across each computer.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
