		<link>http://androw.is/blog/line-roads-with-snow-sculptures</link>
		<comments>http://androw.is/blog/line-roads-with-snow-sculptures#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 31 Dec 2009 02:45:09 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Andrew AbuMoussa</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Mental Graffiti]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[art]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[roads]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[sculptures]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[snow]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://androwis.com/blog/?p=37</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[These should be everywhere...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The last thing running through most of our minds during a snow storm are local aesthetics.  Sure having the world turn white is exciting for the first few glances, hours, or evenings, but after that the reality doesn&#8217;t seem so bright.  As obligations begin to pile the next thing we find ourselves thinking about becomes transportation (read: road conditions).  As city workers slave to clear the roads and municipal parking lots, often generating massive piles of snow, a huge artistic potential is lost with inactivity.  The sides of the road become unsightly as dirt and oil stain the bright white mounds outlining the pavement.</p>
<p>But, imagine then that cities or building complexes allowed artists to showcase their talent by putting these mounds of snow to use.  I know anyone interested in beautifying my driveway is more than welcome.  I just think it&#8217;d make winter that much more awesome/festive/beautiful.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
